    {
      "id": "1e770fc23a796962211a4fd6a5c19d249a89d832",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-02-03 22:22:08.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nNote that we do not need to have llog cookie at all anymore. While this might be sent from the old client, that will only happen in response to an RPC from the MDS to start with.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "90410523592007c1e9a85d3870061c688f31196a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 176,
        "name": "Liang Zhen",
        "email": "liang.zhen@intel.com",
        "username": "liangzhen",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-02-04 01:00:36.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nso we don't even need llog cookie for all replies?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "bf735e56a35a37182421cf35b5651a527766f9b0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-02-05 23:19:37.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\nI was going to mark this +2, but I'm not sure it can land until LU-2432 is also addressed by reducing MDS_NBUFS for the portals that have large request buffer sizes.\n\nAs for the question of buffer space for cookies - this is needed on the 2.4 client request and reply size for interoperability with older MDSes.  The cookie buffer is not needed on the 2.4 server request or reply buffers, though it may not be easy to separate them.\n\nIf it is difficult to separate them in this way, we can keep the cookie buffer, but make a clear comment that this is only needed for client interoperability with 2.3 and earlier MDSes and can be removed in the future when we no longer need such interoperability.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "4f01af1098759a71c26dc1a387ae192cebf5d330",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 176,
        "name": "Liang Zhen",
        "email": "liang.zhen@intel.com",
        "username": "liangzhen",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-02-06 10:49:03.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5: (1 inline comment)\n\nI think these macros will only affect server side\n a) incoming request from client;\n b) outgoing reply to client, it is for emergency only (lustre_get_emerg_rs, actually we only pre-allocated one for each service or service CPT, is this correct?).\n\nClient side request and reply buffer are calculated and allocated at runtime, so it's accurate size, not pre-defined by macros.\n\nSo I think we can just decrease both request & reply buffer size for server side.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "478aff7057d88abd33a6e73d6eb7667118073b9e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-02-08 19:17:00.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nLiang, I'm thinking that something like:\n\n #define MDS_NBUFS min(128, num_cores + 64)\n\nis enough, so that each core can work on a buffer, and there are enough to get filled by incoming requests.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "83d117a2ba9cba1e6ec4e3cda060fd6ec78d4549",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 176,
        "name": "Liang Zhen",
        "email": "liang.zhen@intel.com",
        "username": "liangzhen",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-02-22 04:52:16.000000000",
      "message": "Uploaded patch set 6.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "9641b1145708ffcebd442acf1994cd0bc8cf80a8",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 2,
        "name": "Jenkins",
        "username": "hudson",
        "inactive": true
